Definition: Metagenome assembled genome (MAG) identifier for all metagenomic information. The asterisks (*) before and after indicates any unique identification information associated with the bin; see the Bin Id entry for specific details. When these identifiers appear as columns in annotation files the numbers refer to counts of a given gene or annotation in that genome.
Number of base pairs that were non-standard (e.g. Ns). This column header is the default output for CheckM.
Number of contigs within the metagenomic assembled genome (MAG) (typically matches the # scaffolds). This column header is the default output for CheckM.
The number of genomes used in CheckM completeness assessments. This column header is the default output for CheckM.
The number of marker sets used in the CheckM analyses. This column header is the default output for CheckM.
The number of marker genes used in CheckM analyses. This column header is the default output for CheckM.
Number of predicted genes. This column header is the default output for CheckM.
Number of scaffolds within the metagenomic assembled genome (MAG). This column header is the default output for CheckM.
Number of marker genes matched 0 times. This column header is the default output for CheckM.

Default column header for Pandas Index in .csv files written by Pandas .to_csv(). For generality Pandas Index values are often read as text. These values are not used in the analysis and are output by default.

Percent clay (calculated using 1.5 hour and 24 hour hydrometer readings). 5-digit prefix typically refers to a US Geological Survey (USGS) parameter code in the column headers of this data package. The USGS does not have a parameter code for clay that is appropriate so 00000 is used as a placeholder to keep column name formats consistent.

Percent coarse sand (less than 2000 micrometers and greater than 500 micrometers). 5-digit prefix typically refers to a US Geological Survey (USGS) parameter code in the column headers of this data package. The USGS does not have a parameter code for sand that is appropriate so 00000 is used as a placeholder to keep column name formats consistent.

Percent fine sand (less than 250 micrometers and greater than 53 micrometers). 5-digit prefix typically refers to a US Geological Survey (USGS) parameter code in the column headers of this data package. The USGS does not have a parameter code for sand that is appropriate so 00000 is used as a placeholder to keep column name formats consistent.

Percent medium sand (less than 500 micrometers and greater than 250 micrometers). 5-digit prefix typically refers to a US Geological Survey (USGS) parameter code in the column headers of this data package. The USGS does not have a parameter code for sand that is appropriate so 00000 is used as a placeholder to keep column name formats consistent.

Percent silt (calculated as 100 - (percent sand + percent clay)). 5-digit prefix typically refers to a US Geological Survey (USGS) parameter code in the column headers of this data package. The USGS does not have a parameter code for silt that is appropriate so 00000 is used as a placeholder to keep column name formats consistent.

Percent total sand (calculated from sum of fine; medium; and coarse sand). 5-digit prefix typically refers to a US Geological Survey (USGS) parameter code in the column headers of this data package. The USGS does not have a parameter code for sand that is appropriate so 00000 is used as a placeholder to keep column name formats consistent.

Identifier for metagenomic assembled genomes (MAGs) - corresponds to the *bin* column. The contents within the column headers "Genome"; "fasta"; and "Bin Id" are synonymous. The unique identifiers allow data to be connected between different streams. The difference between the headers is due to different sources; the original column headers are maintained in data files to preserve the raw format from the original source. Discrepancies are resolved via script and outputs have consistent column headers. Each identifier has multiple parts separated by underscores or hyphens: (1) river name; (2) year of the study; (3) surface water vs porewater distinction (sw indicating surface water; pp indicating pore water; (4) number in hours; (5) WHONDRS indicating relationship to the Worldwide Hydrobiogeochemistry Observation Network for Dynamic River Systems research consortium; (6) surface water vs porewater distinction (SW indicating surface water; PP indicating pore water); (7) 48  to indicate that the sample is for the 48 Hour study; (8) six digit unique identifier; (9) single letter indicating the method; and (10) bin identifier.

Type of grab sample associated with the solid char sample (300C; 600C; endchar; completecombustion or muffle). "Muffle" means char sample came from material burnt in crucible in a closed muffle furnace. "300C" and"600C" indicates sample was grabbed off the open-air burn table around a temperature of 300 and 600 degrees celcius respectively. "Completecombustion" char samples were ash grab samples from the burn table in-which visually all vegetation had been consumed in the burn. "Endchar" was a homogenized sample of all the remaining char on the burn table after the burn. See BSLE_Burn_Protocol.pdf for more information.

Mean total suspended solids. 5-digit prefix refers to a US Geological Survey parameter code. For each sampling event (e.g. SPS_005_TSS) the NPOC values of each of the three biological replicates (e.g. SPS_005_TSS-1; SPS_005_TSS-2; SPS_005_TSS-3) are averaged. Any replicate values that were identified as an outlier or were above/below the limit of detection are not included in the mean. Outliers were identified using distance based outlier detection. If the set of replicates had a coefficient of variation of 30 percent or higher the outlier was identified by calculating the distance between each of the replicates. The replicate with the highest distance to the other two replicates was flagged as an outlier. The "Mean_Missing_Reps" column indicates if a mean does not include all three replicates using a TRUE/FALSE flag where TRUE indicates one or more replicates are missing from the mean.

Mean dissolved nitrogen [nitrate + nitrite + ammonia + organic-N] reported as nitrogen. 5-digit prefix refers to a US Geological Survey parameter code. For each sampling event (e.g. CM_005_Water); the TN values of each of the three biological replicates (e.g.CM_005_TN-1; CM_005_TN-2; CMC_005_TN-3) are averaged. Any replicate values that were identified as an outlier or were above/below the limit of detection are not included in the mean. Outliers were identified using distance based outlier detection. If the set of replicates had a coefficient of variation of 30 percent or higher; the outlier was identified by calculating the distance between each of the replicates. The replicate with the highest distance to the other two replicates was flagged as an outlier. The "Mean_Missing_Reps" column indicates if a mean does not include all three replicates using a TRUE/FALSE flag where TRUE indicates one or more replicates are missing from the mean.

Mean daily reach-averaged ecosystem respiration rate (ERtot) in volumetric units. Mean ERtot in volumetric units were calculated for the 356 rivers and streams in the Appling et al. (2018b; 2018c) dataset by multiplying predicted ERtot (in original areal units) by river depth for each daily observation; summing new ERtot daily values (in volumetric units) for each site; and dividing the sum by the number of observations for each site.
